        <name>SYN_TaskFunc</name>
        <briefdescription>
<para>Protothread task function. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>A task function receives its own protothread and task descriptor. It must follow the PT_BEGIN / PT_END pattern.</para>
<para><parameterlist kind="param"><parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>pt</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Pointer to the task&apos;s protothread (same as &amp;task-&gt;pt). </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
<parameteritem>
<parameternamelist>
<parametername>task</parametername>
</parameternamelist>
<parameterdescription>
<para>Pointer to the task descriptor (for user_data, delay, etc.). </para>
</parameterdescription>
</parameteritem>
</parameterlist>
<simplesect kind="return"><para>PT status indicating whether the thread yielded, is waiting, or exited. </para>
</simplesect>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
        <inbodydescription>
        </inbodydescription>
        <location file="src/syntropic/sched/syn_task.h" line="57" column="9" bodyfile="src/syntropic/sched/syn_task.h" bodystart="57" bodyend="-1"/>
      </memberdef>
    </sectiondef>
    <briefdescription>
<para>Task descriptor for the cooperative scheduler. </para>
    </briefdescription>
    <detaileddescription>
<para>Defines the task control block (<ref refid="structSYN__Task" kindref="compound">SYN_Task</ref>) that pairs a protothread with scheduling metadata: priority, state, name, delay target, and optional event-wait fields for true blocking.</para>
<para>Tasks are caller-owned — you allocate them however you like (static array, global, on the stack). The scheduler just takes a pointer to your array. </para>
    </detaileddescription>
